Wei Huang,12,13 Ranajit Chakraborty,3 Zhu Chen, 12,13 Li Jin1,3,13 † |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
To test the hypotheses of modern human origin in East Asia, we sampled 12,127 |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
male individuals from 163 populations and typed for three Y chromosome |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
biallelic markers (YAP, M89, and M130). All the individuals carried a mutation |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
at one of the three sites. These three mutations (YAP+, M89T, and M130T) |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
coalesce to another mutation (M168T), which originated in Africa about 35,000 |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
to 89,000 years ago. Therefore, the data do not support even a minimal in situ |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
hominid contribution in the origin of anatomically modern humans in East Asia. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
www.sciencemag.org SCIENCE VOL 292 11 MAY 2001	1151 |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_none xmlPic_yes xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
It was argued that the extensive genetic data |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
supporting the Out-of-Africa hypothesis could |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
also be explained by the multiregional hypoth- |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
esis under a version of the trellis model (23). |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
This model suggests that a multiregional evo- |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
lutionary paradigm is shared across the human |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
range by frequent gene exchanges between con- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tinental populations since Homo erectus came |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
out of Africa about 1 million years ago (23). It |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
is difficult to test the trellis model with markers |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
from mitochondrial hypervariable region (D- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
loop) and autosome because these markers |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
show frequent recurrent mutations and/or re- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
combination (24, 25), respectively. However, |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
this can be circumvented by the application of a |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
large number of Y chromosome biallelic mark- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
ers, which escape recombination and have a |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
low mutation rate. It has been shown that all the |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Y chromosome haplotypes found outside Afri- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
ca are younger than 35,000 to 89,000 years and |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
derived from Africa (21), although this estima- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tion is crude and depends on several assump- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
tions. In addition, if extensive gene flow had |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
occurred between continental populations dur- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
ing the past 1 million years but before the |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
divergence between Africans and non-Africans, |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
as suggested by the multiregionalists, the an- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
cient Y chromosome haplotypes seen in Afri- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
can populations or even much older haplotypes |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
REPORTS |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
would have been expected in East Asia, which |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
was not observed in our data. However, this |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
observation does not necessarily preclude the |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
possibility of selection sweep that could erase |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
archaic Y chromosomes of modern humans in |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
East Asia. On the other hand, a minor contri- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
bution from a female lineage of local origin |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
cannot be excluded either, which should be |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
further studied with the use of mitochondrial |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
DNA (mtDNA) markers. Because the Y chro- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mosome has a relatively small effective pop- |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
ulation size, it is subject to stochastic process, |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
e.g., genetic drift, which could also lead to |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
extinction of archaic lineages. However, in |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
our study, with 163 populations from differ- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
ent regions of Asia, it is hard to imagine that |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
all of the 163 populations should drift in the |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
same direction. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
Inconsistency of age estimations for a com- |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
mon ancestor with the use of mitochondrial/Y |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
chromosome and autosome/X chromosome |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
markers, however, creates confusion. The age |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
estimated with the use of autosome/X chromo- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
some genes ranges from 535,000 to 1,860,000 |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
years (26 –29), much older than those for |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mtDNA and Y chromosome. However, this |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
difference in age estimation might only reflect |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
the difference in the effective population sizes |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
between Y chromosome/mtDNA and X chro- |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mosome/autosome (three to four times as many |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
as the former) in the presence of bottleneck |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
events associated with the outbound migrations |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
from Africa, therefore disqualifying the utility |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
of the latter in distinguishing the competing |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
hypotheses (24, 30). |XML| xmlLoc_0 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
